## **2. Current Architecture (As-Is)**

### **Overview**

The existing design consists of two independent data flows – **Outgoing** (local to external) and **Incoming** (external to local). These flows are functional but rely on manual scheduling, lack real-time monitoring, and depend heavily on local logs for troubleshooting.

### **2.1 Outgoing Flow**

* Source systems deposit outbound files into **app-specific NAS folders** (e.g., `\\nas\appA\outbound`).
* A **Spring Boot SFTP client** scans these folders on a schedule and transfers the files to the **Enterprise SFTP**.
* Enterprise SFTP routes them to appropriate external destinations.
* Scheduling is time-based (cron/threads).
* Limited logging and no centralized success/failure dashboard.

### **2.2 Incoming Flow**

* External partners send files to the **Enterprise SFTP**, which routes them to **Local SFTP drop paths** (e.g., `\\nas\appA\inbound`).
* The **local SFTP** server writes files to NAS-mapped inbound folders.
* The **owning applications** (not Spring Boot) pick up and process these files.
* There is no automated monitoring or alerting for file arrivals, missing files, or SLA breaches.
* Operations teams depend on manual checks or notifications from business users.

### **2.3 Current Challenges**

| Area            | Pain Point                                                              |
| --------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Monitoring**  | No single view of which files arrived, when, and for which application. |
| **Scheduling**  | Outbound transfers rely on cron/polling; no event-driven triggers.      |
| **Alerting**    | Failures and delays discovered manually.                                |
| **Scalability** | Fixed VM/thread-based app; no container deployment.                     |
| **Logging**     | Logs stored locally; no integration with central ELK/Kibana.            |
| **Security**    | SFTP credentials managed locally; no centralized secrets.               |
| **Governance**  | No SLA-based reporting or historical metrics.                           |

